let and const â†’ Block Scope

They only exist inside the block { ... } where they are declared.

Example:

if (true) {
  let x = 10;
  const y = 20;
  console.log(x, y); // âœ… Works inside
}
console.log(x, y);   // âŒ Error â€” not visible outside


âœ… They are block-scoped â€” only visible inside { }.

ðŸŸ¨ 2. var â†’ Function Scope (or Global if outside a function)

If you use var, it does not care about { } (blocks).
It only cares about functions or the global area.

Example:

if (true) {
  var z = 30;
}
console.log(z);  // âœ… Works â€” z is visible outside the block!


â—Even though z was declared inside the if,
because it used var, it becomes global (visible everywhere in the file).

ðŸ§© Function Scope Example

If var is declared inside a function, itâ€™s only visible inside that function.

function test() {
  var name = "Siti";
  console.log(name); // âœ… Works
}

console.log(name);   // âŒ Error â€” not visible outside the function


So:

Inside a function â†’ var is function-scoped

Outside any function â†’ var is global

âš–ï¸ Summary Table
Keyword	Scope Type	Can reassign?	Visible outside { }?	Hoisted?
var	Function or Global	âœ… Yes	âœ… Yes (if not in function)	âœ… Yes
let	Block	âœ… Yes	âŒ No	âŒ No
const	Block	âŒ No	âŒ No	âŒ No

