âš™ï¸ Promises + async/await
Promise

A Promise is something that takes time (like fetching data) and can be in one of three states:

Pending

Resolved (fulfilled)

Rejected

Example:

const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  setTimeout(() => resolve("Done!"), 2000);
});
promise.then(result => console.log(result)); // "Done!" after 2s

async/await

A cleaner way to handle Promises.

Use await inside an async function to wait for the Promise to finish.

Example:

async function getData() {
  const result = await promise;
  console.log(result);
}
getData(); // "Done!" after 2s


1ï¸âƒ£ The Promise
const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  setTimeout(() => resolve("Done!"), 2000);
});

promise.then(result => console.log(result));
is how we handle the result of the Promise after it finishes.

Letâ€™s break it down ðŸ‘‡

ðŸ”¸ promise
â†’ is the Promise object (something that will finish later)

ðŸ”¸ .then(...)
â†’ means â€œwhen this Promise finishes successfully, do this next.â€

ðŸ”¸ result => console.log(result)
â†’ is a function that runs with the resolved value ("Done!" in this case)

Same idea in JavaScript:

const response = await fetch("url"); // Response object
const data = await response.json();  // Actual data (array of objects)

